My prediction algorithm would have to show an above average (aka significant) correlation between phone addiction and cogntive decline (such as decreased academic success). Plot the dynamic range and exploratory distribution plots (like boxplots, histograms, kernel density estimation) to better understand the data. Explaining each plot:

  • Age

    I chose a histogram over a KDE because age is discrete. The KDE made the visualization multimodal and even more confusing. This visual shows me that there's a roughly equal split between ages of people surveyed and that all the ages are indeed teenagers (13-19). 16 looks to be the most common age, but not significantly so.

  • Screen Time

    I chose a KDE over a histogram because screen time is continuous. The KDE shows that there's a roughly normal distribution of time spent on the device, with most people spending around 5 hrs/day. I chose a bandwidth of 0.15 to provide a little bit of attention to the small minority bumps around 0 and 10. There is a little bit of the tail going into negative time but this is just an artifact of KDE with no meaning whatsoever.

  • Grades

    I chose a histogram for this visualization because I want to group the grades into letter scores. The histogram allows me to see what the disributions look like once they're grouped. It shows me that there's a roughly equal distribution of grades with slightly more people having higher grades than lower.

  • Gender

    The situation is pretty much the same with gender as with grades. There's pretty much an equal split between males, females, and other. Based off this information and the previous 3 visuals as well, the conducted survey was very well sampled and could yield very generalizable results.

  • Social Interactions

    I chose a violin plot here because a boxplot wouldn't have allowed me to emphasize the little bump around 8 hours. While the median and percentiles show me that there's a normal split between how many offline interactions someone has daily, this bump shows me that more people have a decent amount of offline social interactions.

  • Time on Social Media

    I chose a boxplot here because I suspected there'd be much variability in how much time is spent on social media. With a log scale I can see that you're an outlier if you spend less than 1 hour on social media per day. While the median and percentiles are roughly evenly far apart, the median tends slightly more toward spending more time on social media.

It's important to be cautious about these comparisons because the gaming data had only 5 clusters while the social media data had 6 clusters. Nevertheless, this doesn't seem to be too big of an issue if I look at each time across letter grades.

This visual shows that the the time spent on social media is not a better predictor of academic success compared to time spent on gaming. However, this visual does show that gaming usually takes up less time than social media (most people in gaming are in the 1 hour range while social media holds most people in the 3 hour range).

All the letter grades show roughly equal usage for their particular group. In other words, approximately the same number of A through F students spent 0, 1, 2, or 3 hours on gaming (or social media, which would extend to the same number of students across grades in the 4 hour bucket). Interestingly, both the social media and gaming groups show that F students contained the most people who spent the most time for that group, followed by the D students. The A - C students only ever reach one below the maximum number of hours for that group (3 for gaming and 4 for social media). This shows a potential weak negative correlation between grade and time spent on either gaming or social media.

I use the logy scale because very high addiction (10) dominates the graph and squishes the rest of the categories. The logy scale also helps because there are more addiction categories for each grade relative to the times fromt he previous question.

We can see from this visual that high addiction is comparable across all the letter grades. Suprisingly, C students are the only ones that might have a 1 rating for addiction. Unsurpringly, as we have seen in our previous addiction visualization, having a 1 rating or less for time spent on social media is considered an outlier. Also, as our previous box plot showed, most oeple spend 2-4 hours on social media per day. Remember from the association matrix that time spent on social media is positively correlated with addiction level.

Based off this visual, the grade doesn't really correlate with your addiction level for higher addiction scores. If we ignore the high addiction scores (6+), then we can see that each grade has a little more variability in each addiction category. For example, (if the 6+ addiction scores are excluded) a B student is equally likely to score a 2 or 3 for addiction. Meanwhile, a D student is more likley to score a 2 comapred to the C student. Finally, an A student is most likely to score a 4 with no possibility of scoring anything less than a 3. This addiction scale for A students could be the result of them being able to manage their time well and have more time on their phone (which is positively correlated with addiction).

"""
This code is adapted from the example section of the UMAP github:
https://github.com/lmcinnes/umap?tab=readme-ov-file
The main change I make is using my own dataset and only numeric columns for UMAP input.
"""
import umap

numeric_df = df.select_dtypes(include=["number"])

embedding = umap.UMAP(n_neighbors=5,
                      min_dist=0.3,
                      metric='correlation').fit_transform(numeric_df)

embedding2 = umap.UMAP(n_neighbors=10,
                      min_dist=0.3,
                      metric='correlation').fit_transform(numeric_df)

Give an explanation of UMAP dimensionality reduction methods.

The only other technique I'm familiar with (and I only learned about this accidently) that does something similar to UMAP is Singular Value Decomposition. I will try to explain what UMAP is through comparing and contracting these two techniques.

Similarities:

UMAP is a technique for reducing the dimensionality of the dataset. This means that it can take our dataset with a large number of features and basically trim out the ones that contribute the least useful information over all. While more dimensions always provides more nuance and detail, the computational load isn't worth it when you can get a pretty decent representation for much less.

Differences:

Specifically, UMAP is used to quickly visualize high-dimensional data. Andy Coenen and Adam Pearce in their "Understanding UMAP" article explain how this works:

In the simplest sense, UMAP constructs a high dimensional graph representation of the data then optimizes a low-dimensional graph to be as structurally similar as possible.

The authors explain that the high dimensional graph representation is created by connecting nodes with overlapping radii. As the radius of a certain node increases, the likelihood of connecting with a farther node decreases (aka 'fuzziness'). Thus, the local neighbors are well connected while farther neighbors are less connected. This "ensures that local structure is preserved in balance with global structure" (Conen & Pearce).

From there UMAP optimally projects this high dimensional representation into a lower dimensional one, much like a dot product between two Nth dimensional vectors results in a optimal projection onto a lower dimension. The way UMAP does it though is much more complicated via a force-directed graph layout algorithm (Conen & Pearce).

The most important parameter for this algorithm is n_neighbors, which approximates tells us how many nearest neighbors will be connected while making the high-dimensional graph (Conen & Pearce). As the authors point out, if n_neighbors is low, no global sturcture can be captured. If it's too high, however, no local structure can be captured and thus features in the same region of latent space will cluster with far away features, making the cluster meaningless.

The other parameter, min_dist, "controls how tightly UMAP clumps points together" (Conen & Pearce). Thus, a higher min_dist means there's more range in the spread of data points while low min_dist results in high clumping on the points.
